'''Palores''' (''Pyrrhocorax pyrrhocorax'') yw eghenn a [[edhen]] ow kul rann a'n teylu a [[Bran|vryni]], ''Corvidae''. Eghenn arall y'n keth bagas yw ''Pyrrhocorax graculus''.
Yma'n balores ow triga yn Ynysow [[Breten Veur]], [[Manow]], hag [[Iwerdhon]] warbarth gans powyow [[Europa]] dheghow, an [[Alp]]ow, ha mynydhyow a-dreus kres [[Asi]] bys [[Eynda]] ha [[China]].

Yn Breten Veur, yma paloresow ow triga yn ugheldiryow hag alsyow howlsedhes [[Kembra]] hag [[Alban]], mes yn tiwedhes i re drevesigas [[Kernow]] arta.[http://www.gorsethkernow.org.uk/kernewek/newodhow/newod3.htm] Yma'n balores war gota arvow Kernow, hag aswonnys avel edhen genedhlek Kernow yw hi. Yth esa paloresow moy kemmyn nans yw niver a vlydhynyow, mes an chogha (''Corvus monedula'') re vatallyas an balores rag tiredh.

Diwwarr an balores yw kogh; hy fluvennow yw du<!--; ha'y beak yw melyn. Yma hi ow tybri  insects, terrestrial [[mollusc]]s and other [[invertebrate]]s -->. Kri an balores yw galow hir ''"kii-oo"'' a yw moy diblans ages huni an chogha.

<!-- The Chough has a buoyant and easy flight. It soars above the cliffs with wide-spread [[Primary feather|primaries]]; the tips of these bend upwards as it curves and turns, sweeping round gracefully. With wings almost closed it shoots towards the surf at the foot of the crags, then checking itself, sweeps into its breeding cave. A crack or fissure in the roof or sides of a tidal cave is a site for the Chough's nest, and hollows in steep crag and cliff faces are also utilised. The nest is, as a rule, bulky, and composed of roots and stems of [[heather]], [[furze]] or other plants, and is lined with wool or hair. The eggs are three to six in number and laid in April or May. They are spotted, not always densely, with various shades of brown and grey on a creamy or slightly tinted ground. The plumage of both sexes is glossy blue-black, with a green sheen on the wings; the bill and legs are coral red. In the young orange takes the place of red until the first autumn. -->

